WEBVTT

00:01.935 --> 00:06.005
♪

00:10.543 --> 00:15.514
WOMAN: <i>Sometimes when</i>
<i>I look back at all of this,</i>

00:15.516 --> 00:17.716
<i>I recoil in horror.</i>

00:17.718 --> 00:20.252
<i>And other times,</i>

00:20.254 --> 00:23.922
<i>despite the violence</i>
<i>and perversity,</i>

00:23.924 --> 00:26.425
<i>maybe because of it,</i>

00:26.427 --> 00:29.194
<i>I glow with pride.</i>

00:39.706 --> 00:42.007
[door buzzer]

00:45.111 --> 00:46.612
Yes?

00:46.614 --> 00:48.514
MAN: <i>It's your guest.</i>

02:04.691 --> 02:08.526
<i>[touch tones playing</i>
<i>"Here Comes The Bride"]</i>

02:12.732 --> 02:14.399
That's the exit code.

02:14.401 --> 02:17.169
<i>Oh. Okay, okay. Uh...</i>

02:17.171 --> 02:20.606
<i>[touch tones playing</i>
<i>"Mary Had A Little Lamb"]</i>

02:20.608 --> 02:22.341
<i>[door unlocks]</i>

02:23.576 --> 02:25.577
[laughing]

02:25.579 --> 02:28.514
What was that?
That was super weird.

02:28.516 --> 02:31.783
That's one of Alan's little,
you know...

02:31.785 --> 02:33.852
Well, does he ever change it?

02:33.854 --> 02:35.220
Sure, sure.

02:35.222 --> 02:37.656
What if you drink,
and you can't remember?

02:37.658 --> 02:41.527
Was that "Ring Around The Rosie"
or "I Left My Heart"?

02:41.529 --> 02:44.930
The tricky part is
it works both ways.

02:44.932 --> 02:46.398
Both ways?

02:46.400 --> 02:49.001
You have to punch in
a different code to get out.

02:49.003 --> 02:51.803
- Really?
- He rents the place out.

02:51.805 --> 02:55.674
You know,
like art shows, events.

02:55.676 --> 02:58.677
It's very useful
in business negotiations.

02:58.679 --> 03:00.012
Business?

03:00.014 --> 03:02.948
You know, like a merger
or a labor contract.

03:02.950 --> 03:05.250
Two parties
at each other's throats.

03:05.252 --> 03:08.487
Lock 'em in here.
No way out.

03:08.489 --> 03:10.656
You'd be surprised how quickly
an irresistible force

03:10.658 --> 03:13.525
and an immoveable object
start doing the tango.

03:13.527 --> 03:16.628
- Wait, wait.
- What, what, what?

03:16.630 --> 03:19.431
Isn't that... the club?

03:19.433 --> 03:24.069
Oh! We've been tearin' it up
down there, man!

03:24.071 --> 03:28.840
Alan, let me present to you
my niece...

03:28.842 --> 03:31.043
Manya.

03:31.045 --> 03:33.345
I'm charmed.

03:42.055 --> 03:44.089
[knocking]

03:46.960 --> 03:48.760
[knocking]

04:00.506 --> 04:03.942
- Alan! Please come in.
- Thank you.

04:03.944 --> 04:07.346
- How good to see you.
- Yes, likewise.

04:08.648 --> 04:11.216
- Let me take your coat.
- Thanks.

04:11.218 --> 04:14.219
How is it out?
Still brisk?

04:14.221 --> 04:16.588
Brisk?
It's downright treacherous.

04:16.589 --> 04:20.259
Rain's frozen over.
It's like walking on glass.

04:20.261 --> 04:24.096
Well, welcome
to my overheated sublet.

04:24.098 --> 04:26.999
My friend Sheila says the proper
attire for New York in winter

04:27.001 --> 04:30.302
is a down overcoat, a pair
of boots and a bathing suit.

04:30.304 --> 04:32.204
Walk outside,
and it's freezing.

04:32.206 --> 04:36.041
Step indoors,
and you sweat like a pig.

04:36.043 --> 04:37.409
Yes.

04:37.411 --> 04:40.412
- You're looking well.
- And you.

04:40.414 --> 04:44.583
So you, uh,
you moved to the city.

04:44.585 --> 04:47.853
- Columbia Med School.
- How do you like it?

04:47.855 --> 04:50.322
I'm looking forward
to my surgery rotation,

04:50.324 --> 04:52.491
learning how
to use a scalpel.

04:52.493 --> 04:55.794
Why did you invite me here?

04:55.796 --> 04:57.596
Gregory said I had to meet you.

04:57.598 --> 05:00.899
He said you were
a real New York character.

05:00.901 --> 05:03.635
I'm not sure
that's a compliment.

05:03.637 --> 05:04.803
It's not.

05:04.805 --> 05:06.104
[chuckles]

05:06.106 --> 05:08.840
Well, is it true?
Are you a character?

05:08.842 --> 05:10.509
I have my moments.

05:10.511 --> 05:13.945
I bet you do.
And do you boogie?

05:13.947 --> 05:15.747
- Not like that.
- Like what then?

05:15.749 --> 05:18.784
Come on!
I've worn poor Gregory out.

05:20.019 --> 05:21.219
Yeah!

05:22.955 --> 05:24.823
[laughs]

05:28.194 --> 05:32.831
And you, sir,
will you dance with me?

05:32.833 --> 05:36.568
<i>♪ [distant]</i>

05:41.741 --> 05:45.243
- So you own that club?
- Downstairs?

05:45.245 --> 05:47.512
Yeah, I used to.

05:47.514 --> 05:49.848
Actually, I still got
a piece of it.

05:49.850 --> 05:51.116
He owns a piece of everything.

05:51.118 --> 05:52.684
And everybody.

05:52.686 --> 05:53.719
Oh.

05:53.721 --> 05:56.154
You know, I like
making things happen.

05:56.156 --> 05:58.757
And what do you make happen?

05:58.759 --> 06:00.192
I don't know.

06:00.194 --> 06:01.293
Life?

06:01.295 --> 06:05.097
Oh! Pretentious!

06:05.099 --> 06:08.266
You think so? You think?

06:08.268 --> 06:09.668
And what is life?

06:09.670 --> 06:12.804
Something unexpected?
Jarring?

06:12.806 --> 06:15.407
You're startled, scared.

06:15.409 --> 06:17.676
You feel the impulse
to stifle it,

06:17.678 --> 06:20.045
but something else inside
tells you to go on,

06:20.047 --> 06:21.446
to let it happen.

06:21.448 --> 06:23.882
So you take a deep breath,
and you plunge,

06:23.884 --> 06:25.951
holding on for dear life,

06:25.953 --> 06:28.286
and suddenly you find yourself

06:28.288 --> 06:31.089
in some place
you have never been before.

06:31.091 --> 06:34.426
And you're asking yourself,
"Is this really happening?"

06:34.428 --> 06:36.962
Your heart is pounding.
You're a possibility.

06:36.964 --> 06:40.565
You're an infinite series
of possibilities.

06:40.567 --> 06:45.337
You got flesh and bone,
blood, heart, mind, a quim.

06:45.339 --> 06:47.105
And you're alive!

06:47.107 --> 06:49.341
But it's scary, right?

06:49.343 --> 06:52.444
I mean, you're dancing
with your uncle,

06:52.446 --> 06:54.713
and now you're
dancing with me,

06:54.715 --> 06:57.115
and suddenly it's not
just friendly anymore.

06:57.117 --> 06:58.583
It's more...

07:02.088 --> 07:03.388
It's intimate.

07:05.525 --> 07:09.127
Like we've known each other
for years.

07:09.129 --> 07:11.596
And you don't know what that
means and why it's happening,

07:11.598 --> 07:14.399
but it is happening,
isn't it?

07:14.401 --> 07:18.336
Come on, Alan.
You don't want to ruin the fun.

07:18.338 --> 07:20.071
No, of course not.

07:20.073 --> 07:22.240
Oh, would you like--
I've made martinis.

07:22.242 --> 07:24.976
- Oh, I don't drink gin.
- Stoli?

07:26.813 --> 07:27.913
Oh.

07:44.263 --> 07:45.664
Cheers.

07:49.469 --> 07:51.903
So you were pleased
to get my invitation?

07:51.905 --> 07:53.738
Pleasantly shocked.

07:53.740 --> 07:55.574
I promised you dinner,
didn't I?

07:55.576 --> 07:57.242
- Yeah, but that was--
- It's more than a year later,

07:57.244 --> 08:00.111
but under the circumstances,
I thought you'd understand.

08:00.113 --> 08:04.983
No. Under the circumstances,
I don't understand at all.

08:04.985 --> 08:06.551
That's why I'm here.

08:06.553 --> 08:09.087
Well, Alan, times change.

08:09.089 --> 08:10.722
People change.

08:10.724 --> 08:14.326
As you said then,
I was very young when we met.

08:15.962 --> 08:16.995
[ding]

08:20.132 --> 08:21.900
What are you making there?
It smells absolutely--

08:21.902 --> 08:25.637
- Manigot con quattro formaggi.
- Manigot what?

08:25.639 --> 08:28.073
Manicotti stuffed with
four cheeses in a ragù sauce.

08:28.075 --> 08:31.376
It's basically
my mother's recipe.

08:33.179 --> 08:34.412
Mmm!

08:34.414 --> 08:36.715
Oh, this is really delicious.

08:36.717 --> 08:39.583
I hope so. I've spent
enough time preparing it.

08:39.586 --> 08:42.888
I wanted everything to be...

08:42.890 --> 08:44.623
just right.

08:45.658 --> 08:47.893
What? What are you thinking?

08:47.895 --> 08:51.029
I don't know.

08:51.031 --> 08:54.599
What you're doing here
tonight seems...

08:58.371 --> 08:59.938
extraordinary.

08:59.940 --> 09:01.006
How so?

09:01.008 --> 09:02.707
Well, you're preparing
this meal.

09:02.709 --> 09:04.843
- Feast.
- Feast. Sorry.

09:04.845 --> 09:06.778
For me.

09:06.780 --> 09:09.781
I decided not to be a victim.

09:09.783 --> 09:11.249
Very smart.

09:11.251 --> 09:13.952
Yes, I was able to find...

09:15.388 --> 09:17.656
a different perspective.

09:17.658 --> 09:20.191
Different than I had
at the time.

09:20.193 --> 09:22.093
Good.

09:22.095 --> 09:24.095
And what is this
new perspective?

09:24.097 --> 09:26.064
You're seeing it.

09:29.368 --> 09:30.969
Dance with me, girl.

09:30.971 --> 09:33.772
I am dancing!
You dance with me, mister!

09:33.774 --> 09:35.273
- All right!
- [laughs]

09:35.275 --> 09:36.274
That's it!

09:36.276 --> 09:39.077
More! More!

09:42.782 --> 09:45.784
- Merci, mademoiselle.
- De rien.

09:45.786 --> 09:46.718
Wow.

09:46.720 --> 09:49.454
- Told you.
- Yeah, but...

09:49.456 --> 09:52.190
And afterward,
you catch your breath,

09:52.192 --> 09:54.359
and you realize you survived it.
Something happened.

09:54.361 --> 09:57.529
You're not sure what,
and you survived it after all.

09:57.531 --> 09:59.297
I must be drunk.

09:59.299 --> 10:02.901
Excuses, apologies.

10:02.903 --> 10:04.869
What did we have,
like three drinks?

10:04.871 --> 10:07.639
- I'm totally drunk.
- Tell me this.

10:07.641 --> 10:09.007
When people are drunk,

10:09.009 --> 10:11.843
are they not themselves
or more themselves?

10:11.845 --> 10:13.111
Both?

10:13.113 --> 10:14.412
She's very sharp.

10:14.414 --> 10:16.881
- I told you.
- Told him what?

10:16.883 --> 10:19.351
You don't think I'd waste
my time on just any 19-year-old,

10:19.353 --> 10:21.119
do you?

10:21.121 --> 10:23.655
I don't know.

10:23.657 --> 10:25.156
I'm kidding.

10:25.158 --> 10:27.158
[nervous laugh]

10:27.160 --> 10:29.761
Gregory tells me you're
graduating this spring.

10:29.763 --> 10:32.430
A year ahead of her class.

10:32.432 --> 10:34.165
No way.

10:34.167 --> 10:35.867
With a major in...

10:35.869 --> 10:38.470
Don't tell me.
French lit.

10:38.472 --> 10:39.971
Hah!

10:39.973 --> 10:40.972
No?

10:40.974 --> 10:43.241
Art criticism?

10:43.243 --> 10:44.576
Pre-med.

10:44.578 --> 10:47.746
A doctor who can dance.
How liberated.

10:47.748 --> 10:49.748
Well, you know
what Emma Goldman said.

10:49.750 --> 10:51.816
Yeah, she's not really my style.

10:51.818 --> 10:55.053
"If you can't dance to it,
it's not my revolution."

10:55.055 --> 10:57.789
My dear, I think you could
dance to anything.

10:57.791 --> 10:59.958
- [laughs]
- Cognac, anyone?

10:59.960 --> 11:03.461
No, thank you.
I've had enough.

11:03.463 --> 11:05.130
So...

11:05.132 --> 11:07.866
I can see you're pleased
with your uncle.

11:07.868 --> 11:09.501
Very.

11:09.503 --> 11:12.470
And he's delighted with you.

11:12.472 --> 11:15.573
Well, you know, she's grown
since I've seen her last.

11:15.575 --> 11:18.043
- And how long is that?
- Years.

11:18.045 --> 11:22.213
- Three?
- Since the funeral, really.

11:22.215 --> 11:24.482
And in that time,

11:24.484 --> 11:28.219
well, you must have
turned into a woman.

11:35.194 --> 11:37.062
Your eyes.

11:37.064 --> 11:40.065
They're not really a color,
are they?

11:41.801 --> 11:44.869
- Can I kiss you?
- Why?

11:44.871 --> 11:47.605
I just want to.
I want to see what it's like.

11:48.541 --> 11:50.108
Okay.

12:03.556 --> 12:05.156
[clears throat]

12:05.158 --> 12:10.228
Well? You said you wanted
to see what it would be like.

12:10.230 --> 12:13.198
Yes, and I found out.

12:14.967 --> 12:18.203
But you're not gonna tell.

12:18.205 --> 12:20.271
That hardly seems fair.

12:20.273 --> 12:21.973
Fair?

12:23.943 --> 12:26.878
You look different
than I remembered, Alan.

12:26.880 --> 12:29.948
Well, that's not surprising.
We met only once.

12:29.950 --> 12:30.882
True.

12:30.884 --> 12:33.618
Go on.
How do I look different?

12:33.620 --> 12:36.020
You're very suave, elegant.

12:36.022 --> 12:38.823
Well, I try to be.
It's a pose.

12:38.825 --> 12:41.826
Yes, I remembered that much.

12:41.828 --> 12:48.500
But I think in my memory,
I made you somehow ominous.

12:48.502 --> 12:50.535
- And now?
- You seem ordinary.

12:50.537 --> 12:55.340
- A life's work down the drain.
- Just like anyone I might meet.

12:55.342 --> 12:59.010
I mean, you're still you.
You're still Alan, but...

12:59.012 --> 13:01.045
- Go on.
- Well, to look at you,

13:01.047 --> 13:04.682
you'd never guess
what you're capable of.

13:06.752 --> 13:09.154
So I'm confused.

13:09.156 --> 13:12.991
For two people
who get along so famously,

13:12.993 --> 13:15.894
why the three-year separation?

13:15.896 --> 13:17.729
Your college is nearby, right?

13:17.731 --> 13:19.164
Just outside Philly.

13:19.166 --> 13:22.100
So I would have thought,
under the circumstances--

13:22.102 --> 13:24.035
I was afraid.

13:25.638 --> 13:27.872
Of Gregory?

13:31.143 --> 13:34.045
I'm sorry.
Am I being too personal?

13:34.047 --> 13:36.581
I don't know.
I don't really know you,

13:36.583 --> 13:38.917
so I don't know
if I can trust you.

13:38.919 --> 13:41.719
- What do you want to know?
- About you?

13:41.721 --> 13:43.121
Sure. If this is
a game of trust,

13:43.123 --> 13:45.690
then I should really
go first, right?

13:45.692 --> 13:48.993
Go on.
What have you got to lose?

13:51.530 --> 13:53.565
He's very provocative.

13:53.567 --> 13:57.569
Yes. Do you want
to ask him a question?

13:57.571 --> 14:00.171
I don't know what to ask.

14:00.173 --> 14:02.207
I really love my uncle.

14:02.209 --> 14:05.777
I had hoped when I saw him
again, he'd be...

14:05.779 --> 14:07.078
well, like this.

14:07.080 --> 14:09.180
But it's even better
than my fantasy.

14:09.182 --> 14:11.349
That's you, kid.
You got it.

14:11.351 --> 14:15.119
Your father's brains,
intuition, spirit.

14:15.121 --> 14:17.255
- His looks?
- Oh, God, no.

14:17.257 --> 14:19.991
Oh, your mother,
you got her eyes,

14:19.993 --> 14:22.160
her coloring, her bod.

14:22.162 --> 14:24.362
- Hey!
- Don't you think?

14:24.364 --> 14:25.964
I think.

14:25.966 --> 14:28.800
You knew my mother?

14:29.969 --> 14:32.337
Gregory took us all out
to dinner.

14:32.339 --> 14:35.540
Some frou-frou French joint.

14:35.542 --> 14:36.841
Really?

14:36.843 --> 14:39.377
Yeah. They irritated me.

14:39.379 --> 14:41.846
No! Why?

14:41.848 --> 14:44.916
They seemed so young
and perfect.

14:44.918 --> 14:47.986
And they flirted
with each other.

14:47.988 --> 14:49.187
And they talked to each other.

14:49.189 --> 14:51.289
Well, one talked
and the other listened.

14:51.291 --> 14:54.158
And then the second one talked,
and the first one listened.

14:54.160 --> 14:56.594
It was a very unconventional
marriage.

14:56.596 --> 14:58.663
Yeah, they were pretty great.

14:58.665 --> 15:00.064
They were pretty hot, too.

15:00.066 --> 15:02.667
- No!
- They'd have these sex bouts.

15:02.669 --> 15:04.002
No! Eww!

15:04.004 --> 15:05.470
Before you were born,

15:05.472 --> 15:07.839
your mother would
wear your father out.

15:07.841 --> 15:10.575
- Gregory!
- She'd tease him about it.

15:10.577 --> 15:14.345
About how she'd have to take
another lover or two or three.

15:14.347 --> 15:16.381
But it was mostly in fun,
of course.

15:16.383 --> 15:17.815
Of course.

15:17.817 --> 15:21.452
I should think so.
Nobody has affairs in Ohio.

15:23.889 --> 15:27.225
Not where we lived.

15:27.227 --> 15:30.495
So you were just an
old-fashioned American family.

15:30.497 --> 15:33.197
Well, that's the virtue
of the provinces right there.

15:33.199 --> 15:33.998
Provinces?

15:34.000 --> 15:36.367
You know, Ohio, the Midwest.

15:36.369 --> 15:39.704
Here in the city, marriage
exists primarily for sport.

15:39.706 --> 15:41.439
Sport? What sport?

15:41.441 --> 15:43.441
Well, after a while...

15:43.443 --> 15:45.810
You're way too young
to feel this,

15:45.812 --> 15:49.681
but it gets boring sleeping
around when you're single.

15:49.683 --> 15:51.249
- Says you.
- It does.

15:51.251 --> 15:54.052
Society sanctions it.
It's on the cover of magazines.

15:54.054 --> 15:56.287
The thrill is gone.

15:56.289 --> 15:58.623
But...

15:58.625 --> 16:00.758
adultery?

16:00.760 --> 16:02.927
Sneaking behind someone's back?

16:02.929 --> 16:05.964
Stolen moments with
the babysitter or a stewardess

16:05.966 --> 16:09.200
or the wife of some
business competitor?

16:09.202 --> 16:12.003
- That's exciting. That's hot.
- That sounds sick.

16:12.005 --> 16:15.473
Sure, it's a little sick,
but we need excitement.

16:15.475 --> 16:19.043
We need the element of risk
in order to feel alive.

16:19.045 --> 16:21.446
Some people race cars.

16:21.448 --> 16:24.082
Some people parachute
out of planes.

16:24.084 --> 16:25.817
And some people just fuck.

16:25.819 --> 16:27.151
And you?

16:27.153 --> 16:28.386
Attagirl!

16:29.755 --> 16:31.522
Are you married?

16:33.492 --> 16:34.926
Where's your wife?

16:34.928 --> 16:36.661
In Jersey.

16:36.663 --> 16:38.129
And you're here?

16:38.131 --> 16:40.865
I told you. I stay here
a few nights a week on business.

16:40.867 --> 16:43.601
- Funny business?
- It's happened.

16:43.603 --> 16:46.070
- Often?
- Oh, God.

16:46.072 --> 16:48.072
I thought I could
ask you anything.

16:48.074 --> 16:50.508
- You can.
- You're being evasive.

16:50.510 --> 16:54.545
No, I'm just trying to phrase
my answers in a provocative way.

16:54.547 --> 17:00.218
So what does your wife think
about this loft and so on?

17:01.453 --> 17:02.987
She doesn't think.

17:02.989 --> 17:05.323
She has her house.

17:07.726 --> 17:09.727
That's it?

17:09.729 --> 17:12.997
She also has our children.

17:12.999 --> 17:15.433
Three lovely girls.

17:15.435 --> 17:17.101
Spoiled beyond belief.

17:17.103 --> 17:18.469
She swims in the pool.

17:18.471 --> 17:22.006
She screws the gardener,
some low-class trash.

17:24.276 --> 17:26.611
All-in-all, it's a very
satisfactory marriage

17:26.613 --> 17:28.546
by New York standards.

17:28.548 --> 17:31.382
Of course, it's not
what your parents had,

17:31.384 --> 17:34.085
but what they had
wasn't really...

17:34.087 --> 17:36.187
Wasn't what?

17:36.189 --> 17:39.023
Wasn't suitable to my nature.

17:39.025 --> 17:42.260
What's really different
from my memory...

17:42.262 --> 17:46.330
I mean, I knew if things went
as far as they did,

17:46.332 --> 17:48.332
that I must have had
some part in it.

